name: 2-bromo-1-chloro-1,1-difluoroethane
Reason: The base molecule ethane has a melting point of -183°C. Each halogen substituent affects the melting point based on its electronegativity and size. Chlorine, being larger and less electronegative than fluorine, would raise the melting point slightly less than a fluorine would. However, because there are two fluorines, their effect is greater. A bromine atom is even larger and will have a more significant impact on the melting point. Each fluorine might raise the melting point by about 40 degrees Celsius because they introduce dipole-dipole interactions and contribute to the molecular mass. The chlorine, being slightly less electronegative than fluorine, would contribute less, perhaps 30 degrees Celsius. Bromine, being much larger, could contribute as much as 50 degrees Celsius due to the increased London dispersion forces. Therefore, we need to sum the contributions: -183 (base ethane) + 40 (first fluorine) + 40 (second fluorine) + 30 (chlorine) + 50 (bromine).
